  ('partner-pummeling-balance-drill', 'The partner creates a constraint that a solo drill cannot fully reproduce: live timing, shared resistance, external pressure, or a real visual cue. That makes Partner Pummeling Balance Drill valuable for upper-body contact, center-of-gravity management, trunk stiffness, and pressure recovery because the athlete must organize posture, force, perception, and communication at the same time.', 'Belongs in Resilience because the partner creates controlled perturbation, pressure, eccentric demand, or support that develops stability, braking, trunk control, and tissue durability.', 'Use after access work and after high-speed/high-power priorities. Keep partner inputs controlled; the set ends when posture, pain-free control, or safe recovery breaks.', 'The main mistake is letting the partner make the drill random, too heavy, or too competitive. Keep the input matched to the athlete and stop before accuracy, posture, spacing, or communication breaks. Do not surprise the athlete with contact; perturbation is a teaching tool, not a trick.', 'Progress only one variable at a time: partner force, implement load, speed, distance, unpredictability, range, duration, or contact intensity. Regress by removing the live partner input first.'),
