  ('partner-crab-walk-pull', 'The partner creates a constraint that a solo drill cannot fully reproduce: live timing, shared resistance, external pressure, or a real visual cue. That makes Partner Crab Walk Pull valuable for posterior shoulder support, hip extension, grip, and cooperative locomotion because the athlete must organize posture, force, perception, and communication at the same time.', 'Belongs in Capacity because the partner creates progressive resistance, assistance, load, or shared force that builds strength and structural reserve.', 'Use after skill, speed, and power work. Pair partners by size, control, and maturity so force stays progressive instead of chaotic.', 'The main mistake is letting the partner make the drill random, too heavy, or too competitive. Keep the input matched to the athlete and stop before accuracy, posture, spacing, or communication breaks. Do not turn manual resistance or carries into a race; strength work needs repeatable force and safe role switching.', 'Progress only one variable at a time: partner force, implement load, speed, distance, unpredictability, range, duration, or contact intensity. Regress by removing the live partner input first.'),
